03656nam a22005055i 9780520970137DE-B159720191221113333.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||191221s2018    cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209701377 a10.1525/97805209701372doi  a(DE-B1597)518795  a(OCoLC)1031043399  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aREL0900002bisacsh1 aIngram, Brannon D., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut.10aRevival from Below :bThe Deoband Movement and Global Islam /cBrannon D. Ingram. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (322 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- t1. A Modern Madrasa -- t2. The Normative Order -- t3. Remaking the Public -- t4. Remaking the Self -- t5. What Does a Tradition Feel Like? -- t6. How a Tradition Travels -- t7. A Tradition Contested -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Deoband movement-a revivalist movement within Sunni Islam that quickly spread from colonial India to Pakistan, Afghanistan, Bangladesh, and even the United Kingdom and South Africa-has been poorly understood and sometimes feared. Despite being one of the most influential Muslim revivalist movements of the last two centuries, Deoband's connections to the Taliban have dominated the attention it has received from scholars and policy-makers alike. Revival from Below offers an important corrective, reorienting our understanding of Deoband around its global reach, which has profoundly shaped the movement's history. In particular, the author tracks the origins of Deoband's controversial critique of Sufism, how this critique travelled through Deobandi networks to South Africa, as well as the movement's efforts to keep traditionally educated Islamic scholars (`ulama) at the center of Muslim public life. The result is a nuanced account of this global religious network that argues we cannot fully understand Deoband without understanding the complex modalities through which it spread beyond South Asia.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Dez 2019) 0aDeoband School (Islam)xHistory. 7aRELIGION / Islam / Sufi.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook-Package 2016-2018z978311063539308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook-Package 2018z978311066767708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUCal Press eBook Package Frontlist 2017-2018z978311065859040uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520970137zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520970137.jpg  a978-3-11-063539-3  UC Press eBook-Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  a978-3-11-065859-0  UCal Press eBook Package Frontlist 2017-2018c2017d2018  a978-3-11-066767-7  UC Press eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles